<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
<a class="spoiler" href="/questions/894101-spoiler-alert-what-is-the-significance-of">This question contains spoilers...</a>
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Spoiler Alert: What is the significance of the sister, whose reactions and non-reactions are described throughout as if portending some later revelation...but then, nothing? I thought it would be revealed that he was going mad and she was powerless to do anything about it, but that doesn't seem to be the case. And, because they never really speak to each other, I'm not sure why the author included her. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_894101'><a id="like_count_community_question_894101" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/894101?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">1 like</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F220937.The_House_on_the_Borderland">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/894101-spoiler-alert-what-is-the-significance-of">4 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/894101-spoiler-alert-what-is-the-significance-of">See all 2 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/11891868-john"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1462459682i/11891868._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/11891868-john">John</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    I think this is strong evidence for a "it all happens in the narrator's head" explanation. Consider:<br /><br />- Narrator goes insane when his wife dies<br />- Due to <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    I think this is strong evidence for a "it all happens in the narrator's head" explanation. Consider:<br /><br />- Narrator goes insane when his wife dies<br />- Due to his insanity, his sister agrees to take him to live in isolation at the house. Possibly she has mixed feelings about this responsibility, explaining their detached relationship<br />- They get the house at a very cheap price (this was stated at the beginning) because of the fact that it was built over a giant sinkhole<br />- Narrator discovers the above fact and his insanity makes him obsess over it, turning it into a supernatural evil in his mind<br />- Sinkhole collapses, both siblings are killed<br /><br />The sister's initial reaction during the Pig Monster attack seems to confirm this -- why else would she be so scared of the narrator but not of anything else?<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

