    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3215793983" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3215793983" />
    <a title="Dan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5411470-dan"><img alt="Dan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1587053101p2/5411470.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3215793983?book_show_action=true">Mar 06, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dan" href="/user/show/5411470-dan">Dan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5411470-dan?shelf=horror">horror</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5411470-dan?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5411470-dan?shelf=weird">weird</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3215793983" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2202515142894807543">This is a key work marking the transition from nineteenth century ghost stories and tales of the supernatural to the twentieth century Weird tale. As such it is too sophisticated for the former, and rather primitive for the latter. Still, I am happy to have read it.<br/><br/>The influence of its precursor, H. G. Wells&apos; <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2493.The_Time_Machine' title='The Time Machine by H.G. Wells' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Time Machine</a>, is easy to see. In this book we have almost the same plot, only retold Weird style. Hodgson has replaced morlocks with swine-animals, but both come from underground in ord</span>
  <span id="freeText2202515142894807543" style="display:none">This is a key work marking the transition from nineteenth century ghost stories and tales of the supernatural to the twentieth century Weird tale. As such it is too sophisticated for the former, and rather primitive for the latter. Still, I am happy to have read it.<br /><br />The influence of its precursor, H. G. Wells' <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2493.The_Time_Machine" title="The Time Machine by H.G. Wells" rel="nofollow noopener">The Time Machine</a>, is easy to see. In this book we have almost the same plot, only retold Weird style. Hodgson has replaced morlocks with swine-animals, but both come from underground in order to attack above-ground denizens. Then there is Hodgson's long time-travel description, that starts to resemble David Bowman's travel through a stargate at the end of 2001: A Space Odyssey in its tedious lengthiness. Finally, we reach the end when the protagonist disappears to fight mysterious creatures leaving behind only his manuscript. In the final stealing from Wells, we even read a story frame that has two boys discover the manuscript.<br /><br />I prefer Wells' science fiction version to this Weird version. At first, I wondered if it might be because I was more familiar with it. But that's not why. Wells' version is superior, frankly, because Wells was a superior writer. Wells emphasizes characterization and spends time in his story at points of interest for his reader. In Hodgson's version, the protagonist's best friend is a dog rather than a love interest, and his sister, who is supposed to be a key character, is given less characterization than the time traveler's maid receives. Even worse, she drops out of the story from time to time for no accountable reason. There is also very little dialog in Hodgson's book and even more description than Wells subjects the reader to, though to Hodgson's credit he breaks his text into short paragraphs and has short chapters, both of which help make it readable.<br /><br />Hodgson's book has the virtue of being short, about as short as Wells' book, and it is fun to read a mystical rather than scientific premise for the strange travels. Nevertheless, I find the mystical premise rather unconvincing. I recommend this book for lovers of the Weird genre because it is easy to see what a heavy influence it was on Lovecraft, Clark Ashton Smith, and Bernanos (The Other Side of the Mountain). Much of Weird fiction starts here.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2202515142894807543" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

